<h1>Heat Exchanger Setup:</h1>

<p style="text-align:center;">
  <img src="/fa25-portfolio-kam528-ai/assets/images/heat_exchnager_setup.jpg"
       alt="Heat exchanger setup"
       style="max-width: 400px; width: 100%; border-radius: 8px;">
</p>


<h1>Heat Exchanger Details:</h1>
 A heat exchanger transfers thermal energy between two fluid streams without allowing them to mix. The apparatus used in this experiment is a small water-to-water heat exchanger. One closed loop circulates hot water from a heated reservoir, while a second loop carries cold water from a chilled reservoir. The two fluids remain completely separated and do not mix; instead, heat is transferred from the hot stream to the cold stream through the metal wall between the channels. This heat transfer occurs through conduction within the metal and convection between the fluid and the metal surface. <br>

<p style="text-align:center;">
  <img src="/fa25-portfolio-kam528-ai/assets/images/control_vol_diagram.png"
       alt="Temperature measurement points"
       style="max-width: 400px; width: 100%; border-radius: 8px;">
</p>

<h1> Operating Conditions Tested:</h1>
<h2 style="margin-top: 3rem;">Parallel Flow (Control Group):</h2>
Both fluids enter and travel in the same direction, so the temperature difference quickly decreases as they move together. This makes the exchanger less effective, limiting the amount of heat transferred and resulting in smaller temperature changes. In the parallel-flow configuration, both the hot and cold fluids entered the heat exchanger at the same end and flowed in the same direction.<br>

Hot reservoir: 43.1 °C → 27.3 °C<br>

Cold reservoir: 4.0 °C → 23.6 °C<br>
<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Observations:</h4>
During parallel flow, the metal pump block showed uneven heating. The 2/4 side of the pump consistently became hotter than the 1/3 side associated with the cold flow. This suggests nonuniform heat distribution and possible heat loss to the surroundings. This indicates that the exchanger is not perfectly insulated and that some heat is either lost to the surroundings or not evenly conducted through the metal block.<br>

<h2 style="margin-top: 3rem;">Counter Flow:</h2>
In the counterflow configuration, the hot and cold fluids flowed in opposite directions through the heat exchanger, keeping a large temperature difference across the entire heat exchanger. This configuration is much more effective, allowing greater heat transfer and enabling the cold outlet to approach the hot inlet temperature more closely.<br>

Hot reservoir: 43.1 °C → 23.0 °C<br>

Cold reservoir: 6.3 °C → 28.1 °C<br>
<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Observations:</h4>
The hot reservoir temperature increased rapidly to approximately 44.5 °C shortly after flow initiation before cooling. Notably, the cold reservoir became hotter than the hot reservoir outlet, while the hot stream exited colder than the cold stream. This temperature crossover is only possible in a counterflow heat exchanger and demonstrates its higher thermal effectiveness compared to parallel flow.<br>

<h2 style="margin-top: 3rem;">Parallel Flow with Higher Hot Inlet Temperature:</h2>
This trial repeated the parallel-flow configuration with a higher initial temperature in the hot reservoir. A higher hot inlet temperature is supposed to increase the driving temperature difference and raises the heat-transfer rate. Lowering it weakens heat transfer and reduces cold-side heating.<br>

Hot reservoir: 50.0 °C → 30.0 °C<br>

Cold reservoir: 4.0 °C → 23.0 °C<br>
<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Observations:</h4>
Increasing the initial hot reservoir temperature increased the overall temperature driving force but did not produce dramatic changes in exchanger behavior compared to the baseline parallel-flow case.<br>

<h2 style="margin-top: 3rem;">Change of Relative Flow Rate (Reduced Hot-Side Flow Rate):</h2>
In this experiment, the hot-side tubing was pinched to reduce the hot-side mass flow rate while maintaining approximately the same cold-side flow. The side with the lower flow rate experiences a larger temperature change and becomes the limiting stream. The higher-flow stream changes temperature less because it carries more thermal mass.<br>

Hot reservoir: 42.4 °C → 26.5 °C<br>

Cold reservoir: 9.6 °C → 24.9 °C<br>
<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Observations:</h4>
There was significantly less hot liquid in the hot-side tubing compared to the cold-side tubing. The reduced hot mass flow resulted in a larger temperature drop on the hot side in order to transfer sufficient heat to the cold stream.<br>

