  </a>
  for the manufacturer specifications.
</p>

The energy balance calculations show that the total heat transfer for each operating condition is not zero, indicating measurable heat loss to the surroundings rather than an ideal, perfectly insulated system. In the parallel-flow case, the imbalance between the heat lost by the hot stream and the heat gained by the cold stream resulted in a negative total heat transfer rate, confirming environmental heat loss. The counterflow configuration exhibited a larger magnitude of heat transfer, consistent with its higher thermal effectiveness, but still showed nonzero net heat transfer, further supporting the presence of external heat losses. Entropy generation calculations for all configurations were positive, satisfying the second law of thermodynamics and confirming the irreversibility of the heat exchange process. Variations in entropy generation between cases reflected changes in temperature gradients and mass flow rates, with larger temperature differences and reduced hot-side flow leading to increased irreversibility. Overall, the calculations quantitatively demonstrate how real heat exchangers deviate from ideal behavior due to heat losses and entropy generation.<br>

<h1 style="margin-top: 3rem;">Conclusion</h1>
This report analyzed a small water heat exchanger using experimental measurements and supporting energy and entropy balance calculations under multiple operating conditions. The results showed effective heat transfer from the hot reservoir to the cold reservoir, with differences in performance depending on flow configuration and operating parameters. Real world heat exchangers similar to this system are widely used in HVAC systems, refrigeration units, automotive radiators, power plants, and industrial processing equipment, where controlled heat transfer is essential for efficient operation.<br>

The analysis also demonstrated that the heat exchanger did not operate in a perfectly adiabatic manner, as measurable heat loss to the surroundings was observed, influencing overall performance and efficiency in practical applications. While the system approached steady-state operation during testing, temperature drift in the reservoirs indicated that true steady state was not fully achieved; improved insulation, longer run times, or larger reservoirs could help reach steady state. Additionally, kinetic energy changes between inlet and outlet flows were assumed negligible due to low flow velocities and minimal changes in flow area, making this assumption reasonable for the system studied.<br>








